        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> The top-right image on that page is <b>really</b> scary.  The windows are occupying practically the entire screen.  It looks like it'd be horrific to try to play like that!</P><P>Everquest's interface has been desperately in need of reworking for a long time.  I started playing a little over a year ago and almost gave up, because the interface made everything much more difficult than it needed to be.  <i>(And why in the name of sanity are they <b>still</b> binding the attack key to 'a'???  (My first death was at the hands of one of my guild trainers, because of this.  I read about the danger of leaving attack bound to 'a'.  "Hah!  I'm not so foolish as to forget to hit &lt;ENTER&gt; before I type,"  I thought.  And I wasn't.  But reflex from playing Unreal Tournament kicked in and I hit 'a' to turn to the left.  <font color=red><b><font size=4>Bang!</font id=size4></b></font id=red>  Punched and instantly vaporised in a cloud of red mist, with a coupla hundred points of damage left over to spare!  Time to rebind that stupid key.))</i></P><P>The funny thing is, it doesn't really seem to add much for most experienced players.  The spell gems are all well and good, but personally, it's been a long time since I clicked on a gem, to cast a spell.  Isn't this the case for most people?  <i>(I left this post open and have cooked and eaten and in the meantime, considerable support for the whole clicking of spell gems has appeared.  I guessed wrong, it seems.  Still, I personally feel like I have better control using the keyboard.  *Shrug*)</i>  Equally, new icons for spells is pretty, but how often do you forget which spells you have?</P><P>However, the pet HP bar should be a <b>huge</b> bonus to pretty much all pet classes.  Having said which, I think maybe it'd have been better if it'd been given it's own bar.  <i>(It could've toggled, like the AA bar, so only pet classes actually see it.)</i>  Plus, the movable spellbook is sorta novel.  If only because judging from the various images, at high resolution, it should only occupy about a quarter of the screen!  Yay!</P><P>The inventory screen looks suspiciously like someone in the development team was playing a lot of Diablo, at design time.</P><P>Xzzy:</P><P>There's not a hope in hell of an XML interface that you can create your own themes for.  There's just no justification for it, in terms of the percentage of the user base, who'd be able to use it.  You'd probably be lucky if there were half a dozen people per server who could use it.  <i>(Actually, it occurs to me that even if people couldn't write valid XML, they could probably manage to substitute images and resize bits and pieces.  I still can't see it happening though.)</i>  Besides which, given the whole paranoia about hacking and such, I'd be very suprised if Verant even considered allowing people to fiddle around inside the interface.</P><P>Oshii:</P><P>Actually, people wouldn't complain if they got, "exactly what they want, when they want it, and how they want it!"  But that's not a valid comparison here, since this isn't what people are getting.  The biggest problem is that the interface has been being hyped for so long it was inevitable that many people would be dissapointed.  <i>(Most of us bought Luclin over six months ago and it should've been in that anyhow, remember.)</i>  It's the whole same thing as Episode One.  It was an adequate, if not spectacular film.  But after the hype, it looked weak.  Too much hype is always bad for a product.</P><P>Anyhow...</P><P>I'm more interested in seeing the Bazaar go live, than the interface.  But, on the upside, in the Scott Hartman interview, he said it'd go either with the interface, or within a few weeks, so hopefully it's almost here!</P><P></P><P><center>....................AlAaraaf ~ 0 ~ Burynaibane....................<BR>.............................Priest of the Faceless................